":"1453","1310":"1310","28 February 1347":"28 February 1347","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1306":"1306","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Tullibardine, Perthshire, Scotland":"Tullibardine, Perthshire, Scotland","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Tullibardine, Blackford, Perth, Scotland":"Tullibardine, Perthshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Murray","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Moray in northeastern Scotland, which derives from Celtic <i>mori-</i> ‘sea’ + <i>treb-</i> ‘settlement’. The founder of the Scottish house of Murray was a Fleming named Freskin who was granted Strathbrock in West Lothian and Duffus in Moray by David I. The family took its name from the region in the late 12th century.","Irish and Scottish: shortened form of   McMurray  .","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Muireadhaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Muireadhach</i>’ a personal name meaning ‘mariner’. Occasionally it may be a shortened form of   McMurray  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Murri","meanings":["Probably Scottish: variant of   Murray  ."]},{"name":"Murry","meanings":["Scottish and Irish: variant of   Murray  ."]},{"name":"Murrah","meanings":["Probably an altered form of Scottish   Murray  ."]},{"name":"Murie","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Michel.","Scottish: habitational name from Murie in Errol (Perthshire).","Scottish and Irish: variant of   Murray  ."]},{"name":"Merhi","meanings":["Arabic (mainly Lebanon and Syria): from a variant of the personal name <i>Mirhi</i> of unknown meaning. Bearers of this surname are both Muslims and Christians. Compare   Murray   5."]},{"name":"Murrey","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Murray  ."]},{"name":"McMurray","meanings":["Irish (northern) and Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Muireadhaigh</b> or <b>Mac Muireadhaich</b>, a patronymic from the personal name <i>Muireadhach</i> ‘seafarer’ (see   Murdoch  ). Compare   McCurry   1."]},{"name":"Murra","meanings":["Italian (Sicily): topographic name from Sicilian <i>murra</i> ‘large rock, mass of rocks’ or a habitational name from a place called with this word.","East Frisian: unexplained.","Albanian: nickname from <i>murrë</i> (definite form <i>murra</i>) ‘dark gray cow’."]},{"name":"Murrie","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Murray  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":8,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":21,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":30,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John Murray - Fourth Lord of Tullibardine was born in 1307, in Tullibardine, Perthshire, Scotland, his father, William Murray - III Laird of Tullibardine, was 18 and his mother, Mabel Isabella Randolf, was 17. He had at least 1 son with Mary Stewart de Menteith. He died on 28 Febr